				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">FCEU is really showing its age.  While it does have a very nice debugger, I wouldn't rely on the accuracy of its behavior.
<br />
<br />Everything you need to know:
<br />
<br />
<br />- $2003 sets the OAM address
<br />
<br />- $2004 copies a byte to that address, then increments the address (on write)
<br />
<br />- $4014 simply writes to $2004 256 times
<br />
<br />- $2003 is changed constantly by the PPU during rendering.
<br />
<br />- Turning the PPU off mid-rendering will leave $2003 in a semi-random state (its state can actually be determined -- but for your purposes it'd be a garbage value)
<br />
<br />- After rendering, if the PPU is still on, $2003 finds its way back to a value of $00
<br />
<br />- Sprite 0 and sprite 1 have a quick where they don't necessarily use the first 8 bytes of OAM, but instead they use the bytes of OAM "pointed to" by $2003.  Example, if $2003=18, the sprite 0 will use OAM[$18-$1B] (same data as sprite 3) and sprite 1 will use OAM [$1C-1F] (same data as sprite 4), and OAM[$00-$07] goes completely unused.  Note for this behavior to be exploited, you'd need to set $2003 appropriately each frame because it gets reset by the PPU (or does it?  I'm still unsure about that).  At any rate, I wouldn't do this anyway and I'd just set $2003 to zero every frame.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

